-- tEmpowerment of Alcoholic Women: The Importance of Self-Help -- tWomen and Literature -- tLa vieille femme chez Antonine Maillet: héritage et avenir -- tA Doll’s House and the Evolving Feminist Agenda -- tPower and Political Strategies -- tLes femmes et le pouvoir: faire face à la musique -- tLa femme et la loi: réflexions à partir d’une étude féministe du droit pénal -- tTokenism -- tFeminist Politics: The Feminist Party of Canada -- tWhat Feminists Should Know About the Pro-Family Movement in Canada: A Report on a Recent Survey of Rank-and-File Members -- tBibliography -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe six parts of Feminist Research: Prospect and Retrospect parallel the female life cycle, highlighting themes such as the increasing power of medical definitions of female experience - including conception, pregnancy, childbirth - and the nature of depression in women. New perspectives are offered on the specificity of the female approach to both learning and teaching and are emphasized in considering problems such as dealing with alcohol abuse and wife-battering. For example, Margaret Eichler opens the initial section, "Reproduction and Maternity," with an analysis of the new reproductive technologies. Making use of interviews and quantitative material, Ann Quénairt and Jane Gordon take up the theme of the medicalization of reproduction, suggesting that it has encouraged women to see the foetus as taking priority over the needs of the mother during pregnancy. This section is completed by Martin Thomas' interesting approach to gender distribution. Feminist Research: Prospect and Retrospect offers a thorough look at the problems of women today, suggesting that society is encountering a period of strong reaction to the feminist movement of the late sixties and early seventies. Marguerite Anderson argues that only the "dynamite of research" will allow construction of a positive route forward. This collection includes essays in both English and French.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAndersen, Marguerite, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBertrand, Marie-Andrée, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChisholm, Jessie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChouinard, Omer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCode, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Tracy C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevine, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevor, Holly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEichler, Margrit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErwin, Lorna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForestell, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGenuist, Monique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlimack, Linda J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLafleur, Ginette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLundy, Colleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartel, Angéline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMelamed, Lanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontejo, Marie France Labrecque Et Maria Eisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMura, Roberta, econtributor.